Station 24-4: core bias current vs. voltate problem
text: Station 24-4: core bias current vs. voltage problem: Prior to about 1/20/2022, the core bias readings were 15 A and about 4.4 V DC. After that date, the voltage readings went up and eventually became unstable. When the voltage readings reached about 6 V DC, the current reading, nominally 15 A, decreased and became unstable. Usually this is caused by a faulty hall effect current transducer. The transducer is showing less that what the current actually is. The control system regulated for 15 A of indicated current (the actual current is higher). If the current transducer is showing too low an indicated current vs. actual current, the AC controller is phased all the way on and the indicated current does not reach 15 A and both the current and voltage values are erratic. The easiest way to check this is to get a DC clamp-on ammeter and measure the current coming out of the core bias supply (up at the supply itself). If the measured value is significantly different than the touch panel indicated value, the current transducer is probably at fault. A DC voltmeter can be used to measure the DC voltage on the big blue filter caps and compare this to the touch panel core bias volts indication. The voltage readings are for informational purposed only and are not used in the control system. The klystron heater / core bias load box would also show higher current than the expected 15 A if the current transducer was indicating lower current than the actual current. If the load box is showing normal current and voltage values (agreeing with the touch panel readings), then the problem may be in the klystron. See attached picture. p.stiles
